         <div type="translation">
            <p><choice corresp="#a1"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1954"/><citedRange>733</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:meunier2013"/><citedRange>167</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">whosever intention it is to put an end to the master</seg></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">Whosoever intends to put an end to the saṃsāra, the master.  (cf 79)</seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:peyrot2013b"/><citedRange>650</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a1 #a2 #a3 #a4 #a5 #a6 #a7 #b1 #b2 #b3 #b4 #b5 #b6 #b7"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:schmidtkt1994a"/><citedRange>255ff</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1990"/><citedRange>36f</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:jietal1998"/><citedRange>83-84</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a2"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">the separation from each other ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a3"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">Brahmā-god, giver of the life of knowledge</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a5"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:knoll1996"/><citedRange>32</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a6"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">the separation of himself ... struck by old age</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a7"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1954"/><citedRange>738</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1957"/><citedRange>248</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1957"/><citedRange>252 and n.4</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:knoll1996"/><citedRange>32, 43, 47</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... || In the M.-tune: || I [am] decrepit by old age and no more able to walk in order to see the good teacher</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b1"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1952"/><citedRange>19</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1952"/><citedRange>49</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1968"/><citedRange>223</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:meunier2013"/><citedRange>148</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... to whatever extent pupils can be brought to awareness by a teacher, (that) I have made you aware of ...</seg></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">Wie vom Lehrer die Schüler zu unterrichten [sind], so habe ich euch unterrichtet.</seg><seg type="sec_transl" resp="TI">Like the students [are] to be taught by the teacher, so I have taught you.</seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:schmidtkt1974"/><citedRange>465</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b2"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:carling2000"/><citedRange>108</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b2 #b3"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1954"/><citedRange>714</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b3"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1995"/><citedRange>62</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">If you [pl.] (now leave me alone and) go to the Buddha, the teacher, in order to leave the house, with many indeed the question will arise: ...</seg></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">If you [pl.] now leave me alone and go to the Buddha, the teacher, in order to leave the house, with many indeed the question will arise: …  (cf 83)</seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:peyrot2013b"/><citedRange>633</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b3 #b4"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1990"/><citedRange>66</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b4"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1990"/><citedRange>66</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b5"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:carling2000"/><citedRange>221</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">When you [pl.] come close (to the Buddha, the teacher, sitting surrounded by a large crowd), then you [pl.] (must try to see) the thirty-(two marks) on his body.</seg></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">When you [pl.] come close to the Buddha, the teacher, sitting surrounded by a large crowd, then you [pl.] must try to see the thirty-(two marks) on his body.  (cf 83)</seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:peyrot2013b"/><citedRange>254</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b6"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1990"/><citedRange>38</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">flat all around like the front of a mirror</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b7"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1990"/><citedRange>40</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">his heels slender. 4. Soft like silk ...</seg></seg></choice></p>
